## Remaining 18 mismatches — CCE string content bugs

These are all inside string literals in the csharp-emitter modules. The
bare-metal text emitter produces wrong characters inside multi-character
string constants.

**Category A: CCE \n handling (9 defs)**
emit-tco-def, emit-tco-if, emit-tco-match-branch, emit-cce-runtime,
emit-full-module, emit-module, emit-match — `\n` inside strings emits
as wrong CCE character (e.g. `s` instead of `\n`, string truncation at
`\n` boundaries). Root cause likely in `escape-one-char` or how the
bare-metal runtime handles `char-code-at "\n" 0` in the IR text.

**Category B: CCE quote/escape (2 defs)**
emit-builtin, emit-expr — `\"\"` (escaped empty string) emits as `\I\n)`.
The CCE code for `"` (position 73) is being mapped to wrong character.

**Category C: Redundant parens (5 defs, normalizer-fixable)**
int-mod, modrm, sib, emit-mem-operand, advance — `(f x) * y` vs
`f x * y` where application has higher precedence. These are textually
different but semantically equivalent. Could fix in normalizer.

**Category D: Misc (2 defs)**
- builtin-names: `[ "x"` vs `["x"` (space after open bracket)
- main: token count differs (19 vs 22)

## Plan for next session

Investigate CCE string content bugs (categories A+B, 11 defs). Start by:

1. Use `codex sem-equiv --show emit-tco-def` to see full normalized bodies
2. Compare the actual CCE codes at the divergence point
3. Check `escape-one-char` in CodexEmitter.codex — verify `char-code-at "\n" 0`
   returns CCE 1 on bare metal
4. Check if multi-character string literals with `\n` get split at newline
   boundaries during bare-metal text emission
5. The `emit-cce-runtime` diff (`57,\n"` → `57,\C"`) suggests `\n` (CCE 1)
   is being emitted as `\C` (wrong escape code). Cross-reference with CCE table.

After CCE fixes, handle category C in the normalizer (strip application parens
before binary operators).

